english:
  title: Memorial Account of My Late Wife, a Woman of the Shin Clan of Koryŏng
  author: Park Ŭn
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I, Park Ŭn, write this account of my departed wife. My lady was of the Shin clan, surnamed "Suitable Woman," with her seat in Koryŏng. Her ancestor was the High Lord of Koryŏng, whose name was Suk-ju—he served Kings Sejong, Munjong, Sejo, Yejong, and Sŏngjon, earning merit through the campaigns of Chŏngnan and receiving appointments as Elder Statesman of the State Council. His posthumous name was "Man of Perfect Loyalty." His spirit is enshrined in the temple of King Sŏngjon. He fathered Myŏn, who became Provincial Inspector of Hamgyŏng, and fell in the rebellion of Chŏnghae. The court honored him with the rank of Left Councillor of State. He in turn fathered Yong-gae, who this past winter departed from his post as Chief Steward of the Royal Secretariat to command the naval forces of Ch'ungch'ŏng Province. My wife was his eldest daughter. Her mother was of the Pak clan of Milyang—the present Left Councillor of State, Pak Kŏn, is my wife's grandfather.

    My wife was born in the year of the Rooster under the Sŏnghwa reign, on the first month. She was raised from infancy in her maternal household. In her childhood she showed both gentleness and propriety; in her play she observed all the proprieties befitting a daughter. Her grandfather, the Councillor, recognized her virtue and loved her as though she were his own child.

    In the year of the Ox, when my wife was fifteen years old, she came to our household. Though born into a family of office-holders, she bore no trace of arrogance or indolence. Upon entering the gates of her in-laws, she fulfilled the duties of reverence and propriety completely. Together with my sisters, she attended upon our parents with such warmth and harmony that they were gladdened beyond measure.

    In the year of the Dragon, I obtained the highest degree. The following year we divided our household and established our own residence. My wife took charge of everything—from weaving cloth to maintaining the walls and dwelling—managing all with meticulous care. She supervised the servants with such strictness that the household became well-ordered and the inner chambers peaceful. Though I am by nature indolent and careless, her excellence in household management has made me seem worthy of my own roof.

    At that time, both my maternal and paternal grandmothers yet lived, and my wife prepared their meals with such diligence that she seemed never to rest. My paternal grandmother, of the Han clan, possessed such high moral refinement that her discernment seemed almost divine. She often said to others, "Our daughter-in-law is truly virtuous." My maternal grandmother, of the Lee clan, still lives in good health. She once said to me, "When you were born, I had reached sixty years of age. How could I have known that one day I would receive such care from your wife?"

    I have never practiced self-discipline; I have sought pleasure in poetry and wine with my companions, never inquiring whether the household had abundance or want. Yet my wife labored tirelessly to provide for my pleasures, ever fearful of displeasing me. When there was occasion to give to others, she gladly complied. Though our household was often poor, she never allowed me to know it.

    There was a covenant between us that has long lived in my heart. I would say, "How I wish that we might grow old together, returning to our native place to build a simple cottage, where we could honor our parents above and nurture our children below, thus completing a hundred years of peace and contentment." My wife would readily reply, "That is my heart's desire as well. As for the expenses of our modest living, I shall provide them." Because of this understanding, whether I obtained office or lost it, neither of us was moved. Our intentions were truly in accord.

    All men rely upon the support of their wives, but I have been more dependent than most. This year, in the second month, I journeyed southward to visit her father at his garrison in Poyang. In the middle of the third month, I received word of my wife's illness. I drove my horse hard to return, but when I arrived, her condition had already become grave. She could not speak when she saw me, and my tears flowed without ceasing. After a long time, she said weakly, "Why have you come so late? I feared we might not see each other again. Who could have known that this day would come so suddenly?"

    As her illness worsened, she wrote with her own hand a letter to my sisters, entrusting our children to their care. She wrote: "In life, I was unable to show proper filial devotion to my in-laws. I pray that my memory will not bring shame upon their house. Now my illness cannot be cured. After I am gone, regard this letter as you would regard me." She finished writing and asked me to read it aloud. When I had finished, I could only sigh deeply. As death approached, she turned to look at me and said, "Be at peace. I am now departing." Her mind remained clear and undisturbed until the end.

    My wife bore six children. The eldest son, Inyangallhap, is now nine years old. All who know him praise his exceptional nature. Following his father's practice, he has abstained from meat for three years. Once, when ill, I prepared him a broth of meat, but he refused it. Since then he has scarcely touched even vegetable broth. The second son, Daech'un, is eight years old. The third son, Daepŭng, died at the age of two. The eldest daughter, Yŏsun, is five years old. The second daughter, Yŏhaeng, is three years old. The youngest son, Tongsuk, is not yet three months old.

    Both my wife and I were born in the year of the Boar. Our youngest son was also born in the year of the Boar, and we chose his name for this reason. He was born with an admirable appearance, which my wife much appreciated. Even in her illness, she sighed and said, "Our son is most beautiful. I had hoped to see him grow to manhood. Will I not live to see it?" She died on the sixteenth day of the third month, in the year of the Black Goat. We buried her on the seventh day of the fifth month.

    Oh, the sorrow of it! The bond between husband and wife is sacred. In life we speak of growing old together; in death we speak of departing together—yet still sorrow remains. From the year of the Black Ox when we were married until now, not even one full cycle of years has passed. Must all our plans for a hundred years end here? Even if we could not grow old and depart together, had we but been granted another decade or two to see our children marry and settle their own households, it would have been something. But these small ones in their cradles—my wife has left them, and in doing so has doubled the grief of their grandparents. This suffering is all my fault, my unworthiness having brought it upon us.

    We chose her tomb in the grounds beneath those of our ancestor, the Former Lord of Kyŏnghwa, in the southern plain of Kŭmgok Village in Yangjji County. I have placed her there on the left side, leaving the right side empty for myself, that when I follow her, we may be united in the earth. Thus, though our days together were brief, our final resting place shall be shared, and this small comfort may ease the endless longing of my heart.

    I grieve that human joy in this world is so fleeting and fragile. How much more grievous that the virtues of those who have passed are too often left unrecorded and forgotten. The ancients said that a funeral without the inscription of a worthy writer is no funeral at all. How could I allow my wife to be buried without a word from those who knew her worth? I humbly present this memorial and await your response. In sincerity, I submit this.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Park Ŭn (박은, 1450-1504) was a noted Chosŏn scholar-official and this is an elegiac account of his wife written after her death in 1488.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Suitable Woman' (宜人) title refers to the official rank granted to women of high-ranking households during the Chosŏn period.
  - key: ''
    value: The references to the 'Ox year' (癸丑), 'Dragon year' (丙辰), and 'Black Goat year' (癸未) follow the traditional East Asian sexagenary cycle for dating.
  - key: ''
    value: The mention of the 'rocking cart' (鹿車) is a classical allusion to simple, humble living in retirement—a romantic ideal common in Chinese and Korean literature.
  - key: ''
    value: The final request for a memorial inscription was a conventional practice in Chosŏn Korea; this text itself serves as that memorial account.
